<section id="open-questions">
  <h2>Open Questions for Community Review</h2>
  <p>This draft is submitted to the W3C AI KR CG for review. The following questions
  are actively solicited:</p>
  <div class="open-question">
    <strong>Q1.</strong> Is the four-step alignment method described in <a href="#method"></a> valid?
    Can it be improved or generalised?
  </div>
  <div class="open-question">
    <strong>Q2.</strong> Is the resulting IDL/HMAS mapping (Section&nbsp;2) satisfactory?
    Are there missing correspondences or incorrect subsumptions?
  </div>
  <div class="open-question">
    <strong>Q3.</strong> Can this method be applied to establish alignment between other
    agent ontologies in the W3C ecosystem?
  </div>
</section>


<!-- ============================================================
     1. METHOD
     ============================================================ -->
<section id="method">
  <h2>Method</h2>
  <p>The alignment uses a <strong>semantic ontology matching approach</strong> combining
  conceptual analysis and logical mapping in OWL. The method comprises four steps.</p>

  <!-- 1.1 -->
  <section id="scope-analysis">
    <h3>Ontology Scope Analysis</h3>
    <p>The conceptual scope of each ontology was first characterised:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>IDL ontology</strong> -- focuses on <em>agent internals</em>:
        identity, capabilities, delegation, accountability, execution context.</li>
      <li><strong>HMAS ontologies</strong> -- focus on <em>agent ecosystems</em>:
        agents, interactions, environments, and regulatory norms.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>This step identifies complementary modelling layers rather than competing ones.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- 1.2 -->
  <section id="semantic-matching">
    <h3>Semantic Concept Matching</h3>
    <p>Concepts with similar meaning were matched using semantic equivalence and
    subsumption relations. Three mapping types were used:</p>

    <dl>
      <dt>Equivalent classes</dt>
      <dd>Used when two ontologies describe the same concept.
        <div class="owl-block">idl:Agent &equiv; hmas:Agent<br>
        idl:Action &equiv; hmas:Action</div>
      </dd>

      <dt>Subclass relations</dt>
      <dd>Used when one ontology defines a more specific specialisation.
        <div class="owl-block">idl:Intent &#8849; hmasint:InteractionGoal<br>
        idl:Capability &#8849; hmas:Ability</div>
      </dd>

      <dt>Contextual specialisation</dt>
      <dd>Used when a concept belongs to a broader system-level concept.
        <div class="owl-block">idl:ExecutionEnvironment &#8849; hmas:Environment<br>
        idl:Delegation &#8849; hmasint:Interaction</div>
      </dd>
    </dl>
  </section>

  <!-- 1.3 -->
  <section id="property-alignment-method">
    <h3>Property Alignment</h3>
    <p>Relationships between entities were mapped using OWL property correspondences.</p>
    <dl>
      <dt>Equivalent properties</dt>
      <dd><div class="owl-block">idl:hasCapability &equiv; hmas:hasAbility<br>
      idl:executesAction &equiv; hmas:performs</div></dd>

      <dt>Subproperty mappings</dt>
      <dd><div class="owl-block">idl:delegatesTo &#8849; hmasint:initiatesInteraction</div>
      <p>This preserves logical consistency while allowing reasoning engines to infer links.</p></dd>
    </dl>
  </section>

  <!-- 1.4 -->
  <section id="layered-integration">
    <h3>Layered Ontology Integration</h3>
    <p>The final model follows a layered integration architecture:</p>
    <table class="simple alignment-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Layer</th><th>Ontology</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Regulation</td><td>HMAS Regulation [[HMAS-REGULATION]]</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Interaction</td><td>HMAS Interaction [[HMAS-INTERACTION]]</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Core system entities</td><td>HMAS Core [[HMAS-CORE]]</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Agent internal semantics</td><td>IDL Ontology [[IDL-AGENT-ONTOLOGY]]</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>IDL describes <em>internal agent semantics</em>; HMAS describes
    <em>ecosystem interaction and governance</em>. This separation improves modularity
    and reuse.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- Formalization -->
  <section id="formalization">
    <h3>Alignment Formalization</h3>
    <p>The mapping can be expressed as an alignment function:</p>
    <p class="mapping-formula">&Phi; : O<sub>IDL</sub> &rarr; O<sub>HMAS</sub></p>
    <p>where each mapping is represented using OWL axioms:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><code>owl:equivalentClass</code></li>
      <li><code>rdfs:subClassOf</code></li>
      <li><code>owl:equivalentProperty</code></li>
      <li><code>rdfs:subPropertyOf</code></li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</section>


<!-- ============================================================
     2. ANALYSIS RESULT
     ============================================================ -->
<section id="analysis">
  <h2>Analysis Result</h2>

  <!-- 2.1 -->
  <section id="conceptual-roles">
    <h3>Conceptual Role of the Two Ontology Families</h3>

    <section id="idl-ontology">
      <h4>IDL Agent Ontology</h4>
      <p>The IDL / s-agent-comm ontology [[IDL-AGENT-ONTOLOGY]] provides a vocabulary for
      <strong>agent identity, capabilities, intent, delegation, accountability, and execution
      context</strong>, enabling interoperable communication between AI agents.</p>
      <p>Main modules:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>core -- Agent, Action, Intent</li>
        <li>capability</li>
        <li>delegation</li>
        <li>accountability</li>
        <li>execution-context</li>
      </ul>
      <p>These focus on <strong>internal agent semantics and governance</strong>.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="hmas-ontologies">
      <h4>HMAS Ontologies</h4>
      <p>The HMAS stack models <strong>human-machine-agent ecosystems</strong>
      [[HMAS-CORE]] [[HMAS-INTERACTION]] [[HMAS-REGULATION]]:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>core</strong> -- agents, artifacts, environments</li>
        <li><strong>interaction</strong> -- communicative acts and interaction processes</li>
        <li><strong>regulation</strong> -- norms, policies, obligations</li>
      </ul>
      <p>These represent <strong>system-level interaction and governance</strong> in
      multi-agent environments.</p>
    </section>
  </section>

  <!-- 2.2 -->
  <section id="alignment-strategy">
    <h3>Ontology Alignment Strategy</h3>
    <p>We define a mapping function:</p>
    <p class="mapping-formula">&Phi; : O<sub>IDL</sub> &rarr; O<sub>HMAS</sub></p>
    <p>where O<sub>IDL</sub> = IDL ontology concepts and O<sub>HMAS</sub> = HMAS ontology
    concepts. Mappings are expressed as:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>&equiv;</strong> -- equivalentClass</li>
      <li><strong>&#8849;</strong> -- subclassOf</li>
      <li><strong>&rarr;</strong> -- property alignment</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- 2.3 -->
  <section id="core-class-alignments">
    <h3>Core Class Alignments</h3>

    <section id="agent-alignment">
      <h4>Agent</h4>
      <p>IDL defines a computational autonomous entity with identity and intent.
      HMAS likewise defines an autonomous actor.</p>
      <p class="mapping-formula">IDL:Agent &equiv; HMAS:Agent</p>
      <div class="owl-block">idl:Agent owl:equivalentClass hmas:Agent .</div>
      <p><em>Rationale:</em> Both represent autonomous actors capable of actions and
      interactions.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="capability-alignment">
      <h4>Capability</h4>
      <p>IDL explicitly models capabilities. HMAS models agent affordances or abilities
      via task/action participation.</p>
      <p class="mapping-formula">IDL:Capability &#8849; HMAS:Ability</p>
      <div class="owl-block">idl:Capability rdfs:subClassOf hmas:Ability .</div>
    </section>

    <section id="action-alignment">
      <h4>Action / Activity</h4>
      <p class="mapping-formula">IDL:Action &equiv; HMAS:Action</p>
      <div class="owl-block">idl:Action owl:equivalentClass hmas:Action .</div>
    </section>
  </section>

  <!-- 2.4 -->
  <section id="interaction-mappings">
    <h3>Interaction Mappings</h3>
    <p>IDL models <strong>intent and communication semantics</strong>;
    the HMAS interaction ontology models <strong>interaction processes</strong>.</p>

    <section id="intent-mapping">
      <h4>Intent</h4>
      <p class="mapping-formula">IDL:Intent &#8849; hmas:InteractionGoal</p>
      <div class="owl-block">idl:Intent rdfs:subClassOf hmasint:InteractionGoal .</div>
    </section>

    <section id="delegation-mapping">
      <h4>Delegation</h4>
      <p class="mapping-formula">IDL:Delegation &#8849; hmasint:Interaction</p>
      <div class="owl-block">idl:Delegation rdfs:subClassOf hmasint:Interaction .</div>
    </section>

    <section id="message-mapping">
      <h4>Message / Communicative Act</h4>
      <p class="mapping-formula">IDL:IntentMessage &#8849; hmasint:CommunicativeAct</p>
      <div class="owl-block">idl:IntentMessage rdfs:subClassOf hmasint:CommunicativeAct .</div>
    </section>
  </section>

  <!-- 2.5 -->
  <section id="regulation-mappings">
    <h3>Regulation Mappings</h3>
    <p>IDL accountability and delegation constructs correspond to normative constructs
    in the HMAS Regulation ontology.</p>

    <section id="accountability-mapping">
      <h4>Accountability</h4>
      <p class="mapping-formula">IDL:AccountabilityEvent &#8849; hmasreg:NormEnforcement</p>
      <div class="owl-block">idl:AccountabilityEvent rdfs:subClassOf hmasreg:NormEnforcement .</div>
    </section>

    <section id="responsibility-mapping">
      <h4>Responsibility Attribution</h4>
      <p class="mapping-formula">IDL:ResponsibilityAttribution &#8849; hmasreg:Obligation</p>
      <div class="owl-block">idl:ResponsibilityAttribution rdfs:subClassOf hmasreg:Obligation .</div>
    </section>

    <section id="policy-mapping">
      <h4>Policy / Governance</h4>
      <p class="mapping-formula">IDL:SecurityContext &#8849; hmasreg:Policy</p>
      <div class="owl-block">idl:SecurityContext rdfs:subClassOf hmasreg:Policy .</div>
    </section>
  </section>

  <!-- 2.6 -->
  <section id="execution-context">
    <h3>Execution Context Alignment</h3>
    <p>IDL describes runtime environments; HMAS Core models environments at system level.</p>
    <p class="mapping-formula">IDL:ExecutionEnvironment &#8849; HMAS:Environment</p>
    <div class="owl-block">idl:ExecutionEnvironment rdfs:subClassOf hmas:Environment .</div>
  </section>

  <!-- 2.7 -->
  <section id="property-alignment-result">
    <h3>Property Alignment</h3>
    <table class="simple alignment-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>IDL property</th>
          <th>HMAS property</th>
          <th>Mapping type</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>idl:hasCapability</code></td><td><code>hmas:hasAbility</code></td><td>equivalent</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>idl:delegatesTo</code></td><td><code>hmasint:initiatesInteraction</code></td><td>subProperty</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>idl:executesAction</code></td><td><code>hmas:performs</code></td><td>equivalent</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>idl:hasIntent</code></td><td><code>hmasint:hasGoal</code></td><td>equivalent</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <div class="owl-block">idl:hasCapability owl:equivalentProperty hmas:hasAbility .
idl:delegatesTo rdfs:subPropertyOf hmasint:initiatesInteraction .</div>
  </section>

  <!-- 2.8 -->
  <section id="layered-model">
    <h3>Resulting Layered Integration Model</h3>
    <p>The combined ontology stack can be visualised as follows:</p>
    <div class="layer-diagram">
          +---------------------+
          |  HMAS Regulation    |
          |  (Norms / Policies) |
          +----------^----------+
                     |
       IDL Accountability
                     |
+--------------------+------------------------+
|    HMAS Interaction                         |
|    (Communicative acts)                     |
+-------------^-------------------------------+
              |
       IDL Intent / Delegation
              |
+-------------+-------------+
|      HMAS Core            |
|  Agent / Action / Env     |
+-------------^-------------+
              |
     IDL Core + Capability + Execution Context
    </div>
    <p>Interpretation:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>IDL</strong> describes <strong>internal agent semantics</strong></li>
      <li><strong>HMAS</strong> describes <strong>system-level interactions and governance</strong></li>
    </ul>
    <p>Together they form a <strong>complete socio-technical agent ecosystem model</strong>.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- 2.9 -->
  <section id="example-rdf">
    <h3>Example Integrated RDF</h3>
    <div class="owl-block">ex:agent1 a hmas:Agent , idl:Agent ;
    idl:hasCapability ex:textAnalysis ;
    idl:hasIntent ex:summarizeDocument ;
    hmas:performs ex:analysisAction .

ex:analysisAction a hmas:Action , idl:Action .

ex:summarizeDocument a idl:Intent ;
    hmasint:hasGoal ex:summaryGoal .</div>
  </section>
</section>


<!-- ============================================================
     3. SUMMARY
     ============================================================ -->
<section id="summary">
  <h2>Summary</h2>
  <p>This note establishes the following formal correspondences:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Agent and Action -- <strong>equivalence</strong></li>
    <li>Intent -- <strong>subclass of</strong> InteractionGoal</li>
    <li>Delegation -- <strong>subclass of</strong> Interaction</li>
    <li>Accountability -- <strong>subclass of</strong> NormEnforcement</li>
    <li>Execution context -- <strong>subclass of</strong> Environment</li>
  </ol>
  <p>This yields a clean modular alignment:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>IDL -- agent cognition and governance</li>
    <li>HMAS -- interaction and socio-technical regulation</li>
  </ul>
</section>


